INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '6740e941-147c-4734-a516-8f93b3bfb5c6',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Seaborn Data Cleaning — Visualizing Nulls, Outliers, and Type Issues Before You Plot$escape$,
  $escape$Seaborn will silently drop NaN values in most plots, which can mask missing data patterns entirely. Before trusting any seaborn visualization, audit your DataFrame first. Use `sns.heatmap(df.isnull(), cbar=False, yticklabels=False)` to get an immediate visual map of null distribution across columns — far faster than `df.isnull().sum()` alone.

For outlier detection, pair seaborn's `boxplot` with `stripplot` using `dodge=False` and `jitter=True` to see raw point distribution alongside quartiles. Outliers that IQR flags but a histogram misses become obvious. Set `flierprops` to style them distinctly.

Type coercion bites hardest with categorical columns stored as object dtype. Seaborn's `hue` and `order` parameters behave unexpectedly when a column that looks categorical is actually float. Explicitly cast with `df['col'] = df['col'].astype('category')` before passing to any seaborn call.

For deduplication, duplicate rows inflate density in `kdeplot` and `histplot`, skewing bandwidth estimation. Always `df.drop_duplicates()` before any distribution plot — seaborn has no built-in dedup guard.$escape$,
  $escape$import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

# Null map
sns.heatmap(df.isnull(), cbar=False, yticklabels=False, cmap='viridis')
plt.title('Null Distribution')
plt.show()

# Outlier visualization
df_clean = df.drop_duplicates()
df_clean['category'] = df_clean['category'].astype('category')

ax = sns.boxplot(data=df_clean, x='category', y='value', flierprops={'marker': 'x', 'color': 'red'})
sns.stripplot(data=df_clean, x='category', y='value', dodge=False, jitter=True, alpha=0.4, ax=ax)
plt.show()$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
