INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '2562e2c5-5ceb-4f0f-8d28-f2a239359f0d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$seaborn heatmap() — Correlation Analysis Without the Boilerplate$escape$,
  $escape$When running EDA on tabular data, seaborn's `heatmap()` paired with pandas `.corr()` is the fastest path to spotting multicollinearity and feature relationships. Pass `annot=True` to embed correlation coefficients directly in cells — critical when you need to decide which features to drop before fitting a model. Use `mask=np.triu(np.ones_like(df.corr()))` to render only the lower triangle, eliminating the redundant mirror half. For pivot-style aggregation, `sns.heatmap()` accepts a pivoted DataFrame directly — call `df.pivot_table(index='category', columns='month', values='metric', aggfunc='mean')` and feed it in. Control diverging color scales with `cmap='coolwarm'` and anchor the midpoint at zero using `center=0`, ensuring negative correlations read visually distinct from positive ones. Set `vmin=-1, vmax=1` explicitly when the dataset is small and `.corr()` values don't naturally span the full range — without it, seaborn auto-scales and misleads. `linewidths=0.5` adds cell separation for dense matrices.$escape$,
  $escape$import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

corr = df.corr(numeric_only=True)
mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(corr, dtype=bool))

sns.heatmap(
    corr,
    mask=mask,
    annot=True,
    fmt='.2f',
    cmap='coolwarm',
    center=0,
    vmin=-1, vmax=1,
    linewidths=0.5,
    square=True
)
plt.title('Feature Correlation Matrix')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
