INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'ab4f6bcb-ca9a-4b58-a390-15f41eb87f3d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Seaborn set_theme() + FacetGrid — Consistent Statistical Plots at Any Output Scale$escape$,
  $escape$Seaborn's `set_theme()` does more than swap colors — it applies a coherent visual system across fonts, axes, grid lines, and palettes in one call. Pair it with `set_context()` to target your output medium: `"paper"`, `"notebook"`, `"talk"`, or `"poster"` scale all font sizes and line weights proportionally without touching individual `rcParams`.

When working with pandas DataFrames, seaborn maps column names directly to aesthetic roles. Pass `data=df` and reference columns by string in `x`, `y`, `hue`, `col`, or `row` — no `.values` extraction or manual groupby needed. `FacetGrid` exploits this fully: it splits the DataFrame by a categorical column and renders each panel with the active theme automatically applied.

`despine()` strips the top and right spines globally or per-axis; `trim=True` contracts remaining spines to the actual data range — a clean finish that pairs well with `style="ticks"`.

For distributions, `displot()` replaces the deprecated `distplot()` and dispatches to histogram, KDE, or ECDF via `kind=` — all context- and theme-aware out of the box.$escape$,
  $escape$import seaborn as sns

sns.set_theme(style="ticks", palette="muted")
sns.set_context("talk", font_scale=1.1)

tips = sns.load_dataset("tips")

g = sns.FacetGrid(tips, col="time", hue="sex", height=4, aspect=1.2)
g.map(sns.scatterplot, "total_bill", "tip", alpha=0.7)
g.add_legend()
g.despine(trim=True)

sns.displot(tips, x="total_bill", hue="day", kind="kde", fill=True, height=4)$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
