INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '10c23dad-eb2a-4075-bd7f-38c162cbc419',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$seaborn Visualization Best Practices — Right Charts, Accessible Colors, and Zero Chartjunk$escape$,
  $escape$Choosing the wrong seaborn plot type is the fastest way to mislead your audience. Use `sns.violinplot()` over `sns.barplot()` when distribution shape matters — bar charts hide bimodality entirely. Prefer `sns.scatterplot()` with `hue` and `size` for multivariate relationships rather than stacking multiple subplots. For correlations, `sns.heatmap(annot=True, fmt='.2f')` with a diverging palette (`vlag` or `coolwarm`) communicates directionality better than raw numbers.

Color accessibility: seaborn's default palette is not colorblind-safe. Swap it with `sns.set_palette('colorblind')` globally or pass `palette='colorblind'` per call. Avoid red/green combinations entirely. For sequential data, `mako` and `flare` are perceptually uniform and printer-safe.

Chartjunk in seaborn is largely a theme problem. Switch from the default `whitegrid` to `sns.set_theme(style='ticks')` and call `sns.despine()` to strip the top and right spines. Remove redundant legends with `legend=False` when axis labels already encode the variable. Every ink element should earn its place.$escape$,
  $escape$import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

sns.set_theme(style='ticks', palette='colorblind')

tips = sns.load_dataset('tips')

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 5))

# Distribution shape visible; bar chart would hide this
sns.violinplot(data=tips, x='day', y='total_bill', ax=axes[0])
sns.despine(ax=axes[0])

# Diverging palette for correlation heatmap
corr = tips.select_dtypes('number').corr()
sns.heatmap(corr, annot=True, fmt='.2f', cmap='vlag',
            center=0, ax=axes[1])

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
